Task 1

A.

Firstly data is organized. Then a bookmaker is chosen and PCA is conducted on the data of odds to check if over/under 2.5 game result can be explained by the odds for different types of bets.This process is repeated for five different bookmakers. The first one is Pinnacle who has oddtypes of 1,2 (1&2 are Asian Handicap type odds), odd1, odd2, oddX (1,2,x are home win, draw and away win),over and under.PCA results for Pinnacle are not so good in that the first four components barely cover 87% of the total variance which means a dimensionality reduction is not so possible. The most important oddtypes are odd2 (away win) and oddX(draw) since they have the largest absolute value as eigenvectors in Component 1. However, as it can be seen from the plot of PCA that this is not a good model to express the effect of the oddtypes on over/under 2.5 results. In the plot, 0 represents the matches finished under while 1 represents the matches finished over.

The second bookmaker is BetVictor who has the oddtypes of 1,12,1X,2,NO,X2,YES,odd1,odd2,oddX,over,under. Result of PCA shows that first component captures 39% of the variance which is not so much again. The most important oddtypes are odd2(away win) and X2 (double chance type).

Other three bookmakers are ComeOn, 10Bet and SBOBET who have the oddtypes of 1,12,1X,2,NO,X2,YES,odd1,odd2,oddX,over,under. And they have similar results in terms of PCA and their results are also similar with BetVictor’s. First component captures approximately 35% of the variance which is not so much again. The most important oddtypes are odd2(away win) and X2 (double chance type) for all three. The plots are similar for four bookmakers which resembles a “L” and vectors of odd2 and X2 types of odds directs the edges of “L”.

## Error in is.data.table(y): 'sbobet_wide' nesnesi bulunamadı

B. and C

In part B, MDS is conducted for five bookmakers again. For Pinnacle, MDS is done with Manhattan and Euclidean distances successively. The plots of both are very similar but the one with Euclidean is more accurate and successful. Also, MDS performed better than PCA for Pinnacle.

The second bookmaker is BetVictor and his MDS with Manhattan distance has three sharp edges which is a bit different from Euclidean. But MDS with Euclidean is more similar to PCA of BetVictor.

For bookmaker ComeOn, MDS plots resembles the one of PCA but Manhattan distance is more spreaded than Euclidean one. In Euclidean, the “L” like shape can be realized easier. 10Bet and SBOBET has also similar results with ComeOn. One reason can be that in Pinnacle, there are less variables than the others and MDS performed bbetter in Pinnacle whereas PCA performed better in other bookmakers. So, we can say that as dimensionality increases, PCA works better than MDS.

Then each channel with noise is displayed.

Now, we can convert the image to grayscale one. Now, we can extract the patches which have sizes 3 by 3.

  patches[[a]] <- vector_patches
}}

rasterImage(winnie,0,0,nrow(winnie),ncol(winnie),interpolate=TRUE,main="Winnie")

#display each channel

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
winnie_a <- apply(winnie[,,1], 2, rev)
winnie_b <- apply(winnie[,,2], 2, rev)
winnie_c <- apply(winnie[,,3], 2, rev)
image(t(winnie_a),col=rgb(c(0:255)/255,0,0), useRaster = TRUE, main="red")
image(t(winnie_b) ,col=rgb(0,c(0:255)/255,0),useRaster = TRUE,main="green")
image(t(winnie_c),col=rgb(0,0,c(0:255)/255),useRaster = TRUE,main="blue")

#adding random noise uniform [0,0.1]

noisified<-winnie
noisified[,,1]<-winnie[,,1] + matrix(runif(200*200,0,0.1),200,200)
noisified[,,2]<-winnie[,,2] + matrix(runif(200*200,0,0.1),200,200)
noisified[,,3]<-winnie[,,3] + matrix(runif(200*200,0,0.1),200,200)

str(noisified)

normalized = (noisified-min(noisified))/(max(noisified)-min(noisified))
  
normalized
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(NA,xlim=c(0,nrow(normalized)),ylim=c(0,ncol(normalized)))
rasterImage(normalized,0,0,nrow(normalized),ncol(normalized),interpolate=TRUE,main="noisified Winnie")

#display each channel with noise
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
noise_a <- apply(normalized[,,1], 2, rev)
noise_b <- apply(normalized[,,2], 2, rev)
noise_c <- apply(normalized[,,3], 2, rev)
image(t(noise_a ),col=rgb(c(0:255)/255,0,0), useRaster = TRUE, main="noisified red")
image(t(noise_b ) ,col=rgb(0,c(0:255)/255,0),useRaster = TRUE,main="noisified green")
image(t(noise_c ),col=rgb(0,0,c(0:255)/255),useRaster = TRUE, main="noisified blue")

#convert to grayscale

graywinnie<-normalized[,,1]+normalized[,,2]+normalized[,,3]
graywinnie<-((graywinnie-min(graywinnie))/(max(graywinnie)-min(graywinnie)))
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(NA,xlim=c(0,nrow(graywinnie)),ylim=c(0,ncol(graywinnie)))
rasterImage(graywinnie,0,0,nrow(graywinnie),ncol(graywinnie),interpolate=TRUE,main="grayscaled noisified Winnie")

#extract patches

patches<-list(NULL)
a=0
for(i in c(1:198)){for(j in c(1:198)){
  vector_patches<-c(((t(graywinnie[c(i:(i+2)),c(j:(j+2))]))))
 a<-a+1
  patches[[a]] <- vector_patches
}}

patches <-t(as.data.table(patches[]))

patches

#task 3 part a 

pca_image<-princomp(patches)

summary(pca_image)

plot(pca_image,type="lines")
pca_image

# task 3 part b 
Comp1 <- pca_image$scores[,1]
Comp1<-((Comp1-min(Comp1))/(max(Comp1)-min(Comp1)))
Comp1<-t(matrix(Comp1,198,198))

rasterImage(Comp1,0,0,1,1)
